{
  "A probability tree diagram is used to:": "",
  "Calculate standard deviation": "",
  "Display all possible outcomes of sequential events and their probabilities": "",
  "Organize data alphabetically": "",
  "Show the mean and median": "",
  "A tree diagram maps out all branches of sequential events, with probabilities on each branch, to visualize compound events.": "",
  "In a probability tree, the probability of reaching a specific endpoint is found by:": "",
  "Multiplying the probabilities along the path from root to endpoint": "",
  "Taking the average of all branch probabilities": "",
  "Dividing the last branch probability by the first": "",
  "Adding the probabilities along the path": "",
  "To find the probability of a specific path, multiply all branch probabilities along that path (multiplication rule).": "",
  "At each node in a probability tree, the branch probabilities must sum to:": "",
  "The number of branches": "",
  "0": "",
  "0.5": "",
  "1": "",
  "The branches from any single node represent all possibilities at that stage and must sum to 1.": "",
  "A coin is flipped twice. How many endpoints does the complete tree diagram have?": "",
  "2": "",
  "8": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "Each flip has 2 outcomes: 2 × 2 = 4 endpoints: HH, HT, TH, TT.": "",
  "To find the probability of an event that can occur through multiple paths in a tree, you:": "",
  "Divide by the number of paths": "",
  "Take the largest path probability": "",
  "Multiply all path probabilities together": "",
  "Add the probabilities of all paths that lead to that event": "",
  "Different paths to the same event are mutually exclusive, so add their probabilities (addition rule).": "",
  "A bag has 3 red and 2 blue marbles. Two are drawn without replacement. Using a tree, what is P(one red and one blue)?": "",
  "2/5": "",
  "6/25": "",
  "6/20 = 3/10": "",
  "12/20 = 3/5": "",
  "P(RB) = (3/5)(2/4) = 6/20. P(BR) = (2/5)(3/4) = 6/20. P(one of each) = 6/20 + 6/20 = 12/20 = 3/5.": "",
  "A tree diagram is especially helpful for problems involving:": "",
  "Sequential (multi-stage) probability experiments": "",
  "Drawing histograms": "",
  "Single-event probabilities only": "",
  "Calculating the mean": "",
  "Tree diagrams organize multi-stage experiments by showing every possible path and its probability.": "",
  "In a tree diagram for flipping a biased coin (P(H)=0.6, P(T)=0.4) twice, P(exactly one head) = ?": "",
