  "What is a probability tree diagram?": "",
  "A table of probabilities listing each possible outcome alongside its calculated likelihood": "",
  "A picture of a tree with probability labels attached to the trunk and branches decoratively": "",
  "A bar chart showing probabilities for each outcome as vertical bars of varying heights": "",
  "A visual representation of all possible outcomes of sequential events, with branches showing probabilities at each stage": "",
  "A probability tree is a branching diagram where each branch represents a possible outcome with its associated probability.": "",
  "What is a 'branch' in a probability tree?": "",
  "A decorative element added to the diagram for visual appeal without conveying any data": "",
  "The final outcome at the very end of the complete path through the sequential diagram": "",
  "A line segment connecting a node to the next node or endpoint, labeled with the probability of that outcome": "",
  "The root of the tree, which is the initial starting point of the entire probability diagram": "",
  "Each branch represents one possible outcome at a decision point, labeled with its probability.": "",
  "What is a 'node' in a probability tree?": "",
  "The endpoint of all branches, representing the final outcomes of the entire experiment": "",
  "The root only, which is the single starting point at the very top of the tree diagram": "",
  "A probability value that is assigned to each branch of the diagram independently": "",
  "A point where the tree branches, representing a stage of the experiment": "",
  "Nodes are decision points where the experiment branches into different possible outcomes.": "",
  "What is an 'endpoint' (or 'leaf') in a tree diagram?": "",
  "The starting point of the tree, where the first stage of the experiment begins": "",
  "The final outcome at the end of a complete path through the tree, representing one element of the sample space": "",
  "A branch with probability 0, meaning the event at that branch is impossible to occur": "",
  "Any intermediate node that connects two stages in the middle of the probability tree": "",
  "An endpoint is the termination of a path through the tree. Each endpoint corresponds to one complete outcome of the experiment.": "",
  "What does 'path probability' mean in a tree diagram?": "",
  "The average of branch probabilities": "",
  "The probability of the first branch only": "",
  "The product of all branch probabilities along a specific path from root to endpoint": "",
  "The sum of all branch probabilities": "",
  "The path probability is calculated by multiplying the probability of each branch along the path from root to endpoint.": "",
  "What does 'multi-stage experiment' mean?": "",
  "An experiment performed in multiple sequential steps, each with its own set of possible outcomes": "",
  "Repeating the same single experiment many times": "",
  "An experiment performed on multiple stages (platforms)": "",
  "An experiment with only one possible outcome": "",
  "A multi-stage experiment has sequential phases (e.g., flip a coin, then roll a die), each contributing branches to the tree.": "",
  "What does 'conditional branch' mean in a tree?": "",
  "A branch added only if a condition fails": "",
  "A branch that always has probability 0.5": "",
  "A branch that is optional": "",
  "A branch whose probability depends on (is conditioned by) the outcome of the previous stage": "",
  "In dependent-event trees, the branch probabilities at the second stage change based on what happened at the first stage.": "",
  "What is the 'root' of a probability tree?": "",
  "The endpoint with the highest probability": "",
  "The starting point of the tree diagram, representing the beginning of the experiment": "",
  "The most likely outcome": "",
  "The bottom of the tree": "",
  "The root is where the tree begins. All paths originate from this single starting point.": "",
  "What does it mean when tree branches have 'unequal probabilities'?": "",
  "The branches must be rebalanced to ensure each outcome receives equal probability weight": "",
  "The outcomes at a node are not equally likely, such as a biased coin with P(H) ≠ P(T)": "",
  "The experiment is invalid because probability trees require equally likely outcomes always": "",
  "The tree is incorrectly drawn and must be redrawn with equal-length branches throughout": "",
  "Many real-world experiments have unequal branch probabilities. The branches must still sum to 1 at each node.": "",
  "What does 'reverse tree analysis' mean?": "",
  "Reversing all branch probabilities so that each path reads from outcome back to root": "",
  "Deleting the root and starting from endpoints, then working inward toward the center": "",
  "Drawing the tree upside down with the outcomes at the top and the root at the bottom": "",
  "Using a tree diagram together with Bayes' Theorem to work backward from an observed outcome to find the probability of its cause": "",
  "Reverse tree analysis uses Bayes' Theorem: given an observed outcome, it determines which initial branch most likely led to it.": "",
  "A student guesses randomly on a 3-question true/false quiz. Using a tree diagram, what is the probability of getting all 3 correct?": "",
  "1/6": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "3/8": "",
  "1/8": "",
  "Each question has P(correct) = 1/2 independently. P(all 3 correct) = (1/2)³ = 1/8.": "",
  "A car dealership finds that 60% of visitors browse SUVs and 40% browse sedans. Among SUV browsers, 25% buy. Among sedan browsers, 15% buy. What is the probability a random visitor buys a car?": "",
  "0.15": "",
  "0.21": "",
  "0.25": "",
  "0.40": "",
  "P(buy) = P(buy|SUV)P(SUV) + P(buy|sedan)P(sedan) = 0.25(0.60) + 0.15(0.40) = 0.15 + 0.06 = 0.21.": "",
  "A quality inspector checks products in two stages. Stage 1 catches 90% of defects. Stage 2 (applied only to products passing Stage 1) catches 80% of remaining defects. What is the probability a defective product passes both stages undetected?": "",
  "0.28": "",
  "0.20": "",
  "0.02": "",
  "0.10": "",
  "P(pass Stage 1) = 0.10. P(pass Stage 2 | passed Stage 1) = 0.20. P(pass both) = 0.10 × 0.20 = 0.02.": "",
  "A company interviews candidates in two rounds. 70% pass Round 1. Of those who pass Round 1, 50% pass Round 2. Using a tree diagram, what percentage of all candidates receive a job offer?": "",
  "35%": "",
  "120%": "",
  "70%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "P(offer) = P(pass R1) × P(pass R2 | pass R1) = 0.70 × 0.50 = 0.35 = 35%.": "",
  "A traffic light is red 40% of the time, yellow 10%, and green 50%. A driver encounters 2 consecutive lights (independently). What is the probability both are green?": "",
  "0.50": "",
  "1.00": "",
  "P(both green) = 0.50 × 0.50 = 0.25.": "",
  "A medical screening has two independent tests. Test A detects 85% of cases. Test B detects 90% of cases. If a patient has the condition and takes both tests, what is the probability at least one test detects it?": "",
  "0.765": "",
  "0.985": "",
  "0.90": "",
  "1.75": "",
  "P(both miss) = 0.15 × 0.10 = 0.015. P(at least one detects) = 1 − 0.015 = 0.985.": "",
  "A restaurant survey: 50% of diners order an appetizer. Of those who order appetizers, 70% order dessert. Of those who don't order appetizers, 30% order dessert. What is the probability a random diner orders dessert?": "",
  "0.30": "",
  "0.35": "",
  "0.70": "",
  "P(dessert) = 0.70(0.50) + 0.30(0.50) = 0.35 + 0.15 = 0.50.": "",
  "A spinner has 3 equal sections: A, B, C. It is spun twice. Using a tree, how many outcomes have at least one A?": "",
  "5": "",
  "Total outcomes = 9. Outcomes with NO A: {BB, BC, CB, CC} = 4. At least one A = 9 − 4 = 5.": "",
  "An insurance company classifies drivers as low-risk (60%) or high-risk (40%). Low-risk drivers have a 5% accident probability; high-risk have 15%. A randomly selected driver had an accident. What is the probability they were high-risk?": "",
  "About 67%": "",
  "About 40%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 15%": "",
  "P(accident) = 0.05(0.60) + 0.15(0.40) = 0.03 + 0.06 = 0.09. P(high|accident) = 0.06/0.09 ≈ 0.667.": "",
  "A game show has 3 doors. Behind one door is a car; behind the others, goats. You pick door 1. The host (who knows what's behind each door) opens door 3 to reveal a goat. You are offered the chance to switch to door 2. Using a tree diagram, should you switch?": "",
  "It doesn't matter; the probability is always 1/3": "",
  "No, staying gives 2/3 probability": "",
  "Yes, switching gives a 2/3 probability of winning vs. 1/3 for staying": "",
  "No, switching doesn't help; it's 50/50": "",
  "The Monty Hall problem: Initially P(car behind door 1) = 1/3. After the host reveals a goat, P(car behind door 2) = 2/3. Switching doubles your odds.": ""
